{"title_page": "Paul Daisley", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name         = Paul Daisley\n|honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MP}} \n|office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Brent East (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent East]]\n|parliament   = \n|majority     = \n|term_start   = 7 June 2001 \n|term_end     = 18 June 2003\n|predecessor  = [[Ken Livingstone]]\n|successor    = [[Sarah Teather]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1957|07|20|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[Acton, London]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = {{death date and age|2003|06|18|1957|07|20|df=yes}}\n|restingplace = \n|birthname    = \n|nationality  = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|party        = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|otherparty   = \n|spouse       = Lesley Jordan\n|relations    = \n|children     = \n|residence    = \n|alma_mater   = \n|occupation   = \n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = \n|signature    = \n|website      = \n}}\n'''Paul Andrew Daisley''' (20 July 1957 \u2013 18 June 2003) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[politician]] from the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] who is most notable for his period as Leader of [[London Borough of Brent|Brent Borough Council]]. After working as an accounting officer and for his own management consultancy, he succeeded in significantly improving the reputation of the council and pioneering anti-crime initiatives. His success led to his election as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Brent East (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent East]], but he was seriously ill with cancer by the time the opportunity came. Despite apparently successful treatment, he was unable to play a significant role in Parliament before a new and terminal cancer was discovered.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Acton, London|Acton]], west London,<ref name=\"Guardian obituary\">{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/politicsobituaries/story/0,1441,980445,00.html |title=Paul Daisley: Labour MP, his constituency was his major concern |last=Roth |first=Andrew |authorlink=Andrew Roth |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 June 2003 |page=25 |accessdate=6 March 2011 |location=London}}</ref> Daisley was the only son of Peter and Joan Daisley. He spent many days at his grandparents' home in [[Hallaton]] in [[Leicestershire]].<ref name=\"Independent obituary\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/paul-daisley-548297.html |title=Paul Daisley |last=Gardiner |first=Barry |authorlink=Barry Gardiner |date=20 June 2003 |accessdate=6 March 2011 |location=London |work=The Independent}}</ref> He went to Littlemore School in [[Littlemore]], south [[Oxford]] then [[Abingdon and Witney College|Abingdon College]] in [[Abingdon, Oxfordshire|Abingdon]], where he met his future wife. He worked as an Accounting Officer for [[Texaco]] from 1976\u201384.<ref name=\"Guardian obituary\" /> In 1984 he set up his own management consultancy and quality assurance company, Daisley Associates, together with his father; he was formally Director of Finance and Administration for the company.<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" />\n\nWhile at Texaco in 1979, Daisley had joined the [[Association of Scientific, Technical and Managerial Staffs]] and became an active trade unionist; he joined the Labour Party in 1982 in Lewisham, feeling that \"it needed all the help it could get\". Daisley was to become a leading local supporter of [[Neil Kinnock]].<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> He married Lesley Jordan in 1984,<ref name=\"Times obituary\">\"Paul Daisley\" (obituary), ''The Times'', 19 June 2003, p. 34.</ref> and the two moved to Sudbury Avenue in the [[London Borough of Brent]].<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" />\n\n==Local government==\nAt the 1986 local elections, Daisley was an unsuccessful candidate in the then safe Conservative ward<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> of Sudbury Court.<ref>\"London Borough Council Election Results, 8 May 1986\", London Residuary Body, 1986, p. 14.</ref> Highly critical of the Labour administration that won the election, Daisley worked together with likeminded colleagues to rebuild the party. Although Labour lost control in the 1990 local elections, Daisley was elected as a councillor for [[Harlesden]] ward.<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> and became [[Whip (politics)|Chief Whip]] of the Labour group after a year. His ward had a serious problem with gang violence among the black population, and Daisley's decision to confront the gangs won him local respect.<ref name=\"Guardian obituary\" />\n\nDaisley was Labour group leader from 1993 and led the party through the 1994 council elections. The Conservative administration in Brent had reduced the level of [[Council Tax]] charged, and Daisley admitted that his party might have trouble fighting the election because of it; he stressed that the council had also increased charges and rents.<ref>Ian Katz, \"Dancing round a double-edged sword\", ''The Guardian'', 4 May 1994, p. 6.</ref> Although the Conservatives did not win an overall majority, their administration continued. Daisley became Leader of the Council in April 1996, when the death of a Conservative councillor placed the Conservatives in a minority;<ref>\"Tories lose Brent council\", ''The Guardian'', 23 April 1996, p. 7.</ref> he negotiated a deal with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] group which allowed Labour to gain control with the casting vote of the Mayor.<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> After taking control Daisley reorganised the council's internal organisation so that departments were no longer failing. Labour won an overall majority in the 1998 elections.<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" />\n\nAs Leader, Daisley took on the role of tackling the crime problems of his borough, declaring that \"thanks to the evil activities of a handful of people Harlesden has a reputation as a bad and fearful place\" and the time had come \"to take a stand against the gangsters who are a menace on our streets\". He put up a series of controversial posters with the slogan \"[[Young, Gifted and Black|Young, gifted and dead]]\",<ref>Diane Taylor, \"Hard-hitting campaign targets gun crime\", ''The Guardian'', 31 January 2001, p. 8.</ref> and set up street crime patrols modelled on those in New York which were briefed by [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] officers  and based at local police stations. He received praise for tackling crime from the [[Commissioner of Police of the Metropolis|Commissioner]], Sir [[John Stevens, Baron Stevens of Kirkwhelpington|John Stevens]].<ref name=\"Times obituary\" /> Daisley was initially sceptical about the redevelopment of [[Wembley Stadium]], although the election of [[Ken Livingstone]] as Mayor of London led to a change of mind in May 2000.<ref>\"Mayor breaks Wembley impasse\", ''Sunday Times'', 7 May 2000, p. 8.</ref> When the council granted planning permission for the redevelopment, it insisted on a [[Town and Country Planning Act 1990#Section 106|legal agreement]] requiring substantial payments for improvements; Daisley became unpopular with the Football Association for taking this stance.<ref name=\"Times obituary\" />\n\nLong before legislation required it, Daisley made the council set up a Standards Committee and bring in a code of practice for councillors; he set up a special website for audits and investigations and encouraged residents to report suspected fraud. By the end of his term Daisley was sometimes referred to as 'the man who had put the \"r\" back into Brent', a statement referring to the frequent nickname 'Bent' used by ''[[Private Eye (magazine)|Private Eye]]'' due to the council's association with corruption.<ref name=\"Times obituary\" />\n\n==Selection for Parliament==\nDespite being described a 'Blairite', Daisley supported the Mayoral campaign of [[Brent East (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent East]] MP [[Ken Livingstone]] when he fought as an [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] after being defeated for the official Labour Party nomination. After Livingstone won, Daisley pressed for his readmission into the Labour Party,<ref name=\"Times obituary\" /> on the grounds that Livingstone had \"gone out of his way to be conciliatory\". Livingstone's election as Mayor meant giving up his Parliamentary seat, and Daisley was viewed as one of two front-runners for the nomination (his rival being [[Mary Turner (trade unionist)|Mary Turner]], a leading official of the [[GMB (trade union)|GMB]] union). Daisley received Livingstone's support in the fierce battle;<ref name=\"Guardian obituary\" /> a dispute about postal votes in the selection had to be taken to the regional party body to be resolved.<ref>Diary, ''The Guardian'', 27 September 2000, p. 22.</ref> Daisley's selection, as a white candidate for a very ethnically mixed constituency, was denounced by the vice-chairman of the Black Socialist Society.<ref name=\"Times obituary\" />\n\n==Parliament and illness==\nIn February 2001 Daisley felt suddenly unwell and was rushed to hospital where an emergency operation removed a tumour in his [[colon (anatomy)|colon]]; he spent six weeks in a coma recovering from the operation. As a result, he was unable to campaign for his own election at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]].<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> Despite his absence, Daisley was elected with a majority of 13,047, retaining the same percentage majority which Ken Livingstone, who had personally campaigned for him, had previously obtained.<ref>\"The Times Guide to the House of Commons June 2001\", Times Books, 2001, p. 97.</ref> He did not attend Parliament to take the oath of allegiance until 14 September,<ref>''[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2001/sep/14/members-sworn Hansard]'', HC 6ser vol 362 col 603.</ref> during an emergency debate on the recent [[September 11 attacks]], the last member to take the oath in 2001, and made his [[maiden speech]] on 1 February 2002 (the last of the 2001 intake to do so). This would be his only spoken contribution to the House of Commons. Having regained his mobility after some months using a wheelchair, Daisley paid tribute to the [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]] staff who had helped him, before speaking about the role of local authorities in helping disadvantaged areas.<ref>''[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2002/feb/01/disadvantaged-areas#2002-02-01T09:52:00Z Hansard]'', HC 6ser vol 379 cols 1160-2.</ref>\n\nDaisley's weight had fallen to seven and a half stone at the time of his treatment, and it was slowly recovering through 2002. However, in November a new cancer was discovered,<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> and despite further surgery Daisley was told by his doctors that it was terminal. His colleague [[Barry Gardiner]], MP for [[Brent North (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent North]], announced the prognosis to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] on the last sitting day before Christmas.<ref>''[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2002/dec/19/adjournment-christmas#column_1092 Hansard]'', HC 6ser vol 396 cols 1092-3.</ref> He died from [[colorectal cancer]] aged 45 on 18 June 2003.\n\nIt would be 12 years until Labour held the seat again, because in the [[2003 Brent East by-election|September 2003 by-election]], following Daisley's death, the seat was gained by 29-year old [[Sarah Teather]] of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. The [[Opposition to the Iraq War|anti-Iraq War vote]] played a key part in gaining the seat. At the time Teather became the youngest MP in the Commons and held the seat and its successor seat of [[Brent Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent Central]] until [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]], when she stood down and Labour took the seat back again.\n\n==Memorials==\nIn memory of Daisley, the Paul Daisley Trust was established in 2003 to raise awareness of colon cancer and to encourage early diagnosis. It also aims to help people suffering from colon cancer and who are undergoing treatment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pauldaisleytrust.com/default.aspx |title=Paul Daisley Trust |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110207111557/http://pauldaisleytrust.com/default.aspx |archivedate=7 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It holds a regular fundraising celebrity cricket match.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.brent.gov.uk/media.nsf/Files/LBBA-273/$FILE/The%20Brent%20Magazine%20issue%20106%20September%202010.pdf |title=Brent Magazine |issue=September 2010 |page=7 |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> The main hall in Brent Town Hall was named the 'Paul Daisley Hall' in his honour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brent.gov.uk/officeloc.nsf/pages/lbb-119 |title=Paul Daisley Hall |publisher=Brent Council |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105235055/http://www.brent.gov.uk/officeloc.nsf/Pages/LBB-119 |archivedate=5 January 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box| before=[[Ken Livingstone]] | title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Brent East (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent East]] | years=[[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]\u2013[[2003 Brent East by-election|2003]] | after=[[Sarah Teather]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daisley, Paul Andrew}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Brent]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:People who died in office]]\n[[Category:Deaths from colorectal cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name         = Paul Daisley\n|honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MP}} \n|office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Brent East (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent East]]\n|parliament   = \n|majority     = \n|term_start   = 7 June 2001 \n|term_end     = 18 June 2003\n|predecessor  = [[Ken Livingstone]]\n|successor    = [[Sarah Teather]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1957|07|20|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[Acton, London]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = {{death date and age|2003|06|18|1957|07|20|df=yes}}\n|restingplace = \n|birthname    = \n|nationality  = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|party        = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|otherparty   = \n|spouse       = Lesley Jordan\n|relations    = \n|children     = \n|residence    = \n|alma_mater   = \n|occupation   = \n|profession   = \n|cabinet      = \n|committees   = \n|portfolio    = \n|religion     = \n|signature    = \n|website      = \n}}\n'''Paul Andrew Daisley''' (20 July 1957 \u2013 18 June 2003) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[politician]] from the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] who is most notable for his period as Leader of [[London Borough of Brent|Brent Borough Council]]. After working as an accounting officer and for his own management consultancy, he succeeded in significantly improving the reputation of the council and pioneering anti-crime initiatives. His success led to his election as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Brent East (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent East]], but he was seriously ill with cancer by the time the opportunity came. Despite apparently successful treatment, he was unable to play a significant role in Parliament before a new and terminal cancer was discovered.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Acton, London|Acton]], west London,<ref name=\"Guardian obituary\">{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/politicsobituaries/story/0,1441,980445,00.html |title=Paul Daisley: Labour MP, his constituency was his major concern |last=Roth |first=Andrew |authorlink=Andrew Roth |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 June 2003 |page=25 |accessdate=6 March 2011 |location=London}}</ref> Daisley was the only son of Peter and Joan Daisley. He spent many days at his grandparents' home in [[Hallaton]] in [[Leicestershire]].<ref name=\"Independent obituary\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/paul-daisley-548297.html |title=Paul Daisley |last=Gardiner |first=Barry |authorlink=Barry Gardiner |date=20 June 2003 |accessdate=6 March 2011 |location=London |work=The Independent}}</ref> He went to Littlemore School in [[Littlemore]], south [[Oxford]] then [[Abingdon and Witney College|Abingdon College]] in [[Abingdon, Oxfordshire|Abingdon]], where he met his future wife. He worked as an Accounting Officer for [[Texaco]] from 1976\u201384.<ref name=\"Guardian obituary\" /> In 1984 he set up his own management consultancy and quality assurance company, Daisley Associates, together with his father; he was formally Director of Finance and Administration for the company.<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" />\n\nWhile at Texaco in 1979, Daisley had joined the [[Association of Scientific, Technical and Managerial Staffs]] and became an active trade unionist; he joined the Labour Party in 1982 in Lewisham, feeling that \"it needed all the help it could get\". Daisley was to become a leading local supporter of [[Neil Kinnock]].<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> He married Lesley Jordan in 1984,<ref name=\"Times obituary\">\"Paul Daisley\" (obituary), ''The Times'', 19 June 2003, p. 34.</ref> and the two moved to Sudbury Avenue in the [[London Borough of Brent]].<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" />\n\n==Local government==\nAt the 1986 local elections, Daisley was an unsuccessful candidate in the then safe Conservative ward<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> of Sudbury Court.<ref>\"London Borough Council Election Results, 8 May 1986\", London Residuary Body, 1986, p. 14.</ref> Highly critical of the Labour administration that won the election, Daisley worked together with likeminded colleagues to rebuild the party. Although Labour lost control in the 1990 local elections, Daisley was elected as a councillor for [[Harlesden]] ward.<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> and became [[Whip (politics)|Chief Whip]] of the Labour group after a year. His ward had a serious problem with gang violence among the black population, and Daisley's decision to confront the gangs won him local respect.<ref name=\"Guardian obituary\" />\n\nDaisley was Labour group leader from 1993 and led the party through the 1994 council elections. The Conservative administration in Brent had reduced the level of [[Council Tax]] charged, and Daisley admitted that his party might have trouble fighting the election because of it; he stressed that the council had also increased charges and rents.<ref>Ian Katz, \"Dancing round a double-edged sword\", ''The Guardian'', 4 May 1994, p. 6.</ref> Although the Conservatives did not win an overall majority, their administration continued. Daisley became Leader of the Council in April 1996, when the death of a Conservative councillor placed the Conservatives in a minority;<ref>\"Tories lose Brent council\", ''The Guardian'', 23 April 1996, p. 7.</ref> he negotiated a deal with the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] group which allowed Labour to gain control with the casting vote of the Mayor.<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> After taking control Daisley reorganised the council's internal organisation so that departments were no longer failing. Labour won an overall majority in the 1998 elections.<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" />\n\nAs Leader, Daisley took on the role of tackling the crime problems of his borough, declaring that \"thanks to the evil activities of a handful of people Harlesden has a reputation as a bad and fearful place\" and the time had come \"to take a stand against the gangsters who are a menace on our streets\". He put up a series of controversial posters with the slogan \"[[Young, Gifted and Black|Young, gifted and dead]]\",<ref>Diane Taylor, \"Hard-hitting campaign targets gun crime\", ''The Guardian'', 31 January 2001, p. 8.</ref> and set up street crime patrols modelled on those in New York which were briefed by [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] officers  and based at local police stations. He received praise for tackling crime from the [[Commissioner of Police of the Metropolis|Commissioner]], Sir [[John Stevens, Baron Stevens of Kirkwhelpington|John Stevens]].<ref name=\"Times obituary\" /> Daisley was initially sceptical about the redevelopment of [[Wembley Stadium]], although the election of [[Ken Livingstone]] as Mayor of London led to a change of mind in May 2000.<ref>\"Mayor breaks Wembley impasse\", ''Sunday Times'', 7 May 2000, p. 8.</ref> When the council granted planning permission for the redevelopment, it insisted on a [[Town and Country Planning Act 1990#Section 106|legal agreement]] requiring substantial payments for improvements; Daisley became unpopular with the Football Association for taking this stance.<ref name=\"Times obituary\" />\n\nLong before legislation required it, Daisley made the council set up a Standards Committee and bring in a code of practice for councillors; he set up a special website for audits and investigations and encouraged residents to report suspected fraud. By the end of his term Daisley was sometimes referred to as 'the man who had put the \"r\" back into Brent', a statement referring to the frequent nickname 'Bent' used by ''[[Private Eye (magazine)|Private Eye]]'' due to the council's association with corruption.<ref name=\"Times obituary\" />\n\n==Selection for Parliament==\nDespite being described a 'Blairite', Daisley supported the Mayoral campaign of [[Brent East (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent East]] MP [[Ken Livingstone]] when he fought as an [[Independent (politician)|Independent]] after being defeated for the official Labour Party nomination. After Livingstone won, Daisley pressed for his readmission into the Labour Party,<ref name=\"Times obituary\" /> on the grounds that Livingstone had \"gone out of his way to be conciliatory\". Livingstone's election as Mayor meant giving up his Parliamentary seat, and Daisley was viewed as one of two front-runners for the nomination (his rival being [[Mary Turner (trade unionist)|Mary Turner]], a leading official of the [[GMB (trade union)|GMB]] union). Daisley received Livingstone's support in the fierce battle;<ref name=\"Guardian obituary\" /> a dispute about postal votes in the selection had to be taken to the regional party body to be resolved.<ref>Diary, ''The Guardian'', 27 September 2000, p. 22.</ref> Daisley's selection, as a white candidate for a very ethnically mixed constituency, was denounced by the vice-chairman of the Black Socialist Society.<ref name=\"Times obituary\" />\n\n==Parliament and illness==\nIn February 2001 Daisley felt suddenly unwell and was rushed to hospital where an emergency operation removed a tumour in his [[colon (anatomy)|colon]]; he spent six weeks in a coma recovering from the operation. As a result, he was unable to campaign for his own election at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]].<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> Despite his absence, Daisley was elected with a majority of 13,047, retaining the same percentage majority which Ken Livingstone, who had personally campaigned for him, had previously obtained.<ref>\"The Times Guide to the House of Commons June 2001\", Times Books, 2001, p. 97.</ref> He did not attend Parliament to take the oath of allegiance until 14 September,<ref>''[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2001/sep/14/members-sworn Hansard]'', HC 6ser vol 362 col 603.</ref>, during an emergency debate on the recent [[September 11 attacks]], the last member to take the oath in 2001, and made his [[maiden speech]] on 1 February 2002 (the last of the 2001 intake to do so). This would be his only spoken contribution to the House of Commons. Having regained his mobility after some months using a wheelchair, Daisley paid tribute to the [[National Health Service (England)|National Health Service]] staff who had helped him, before speaking about the role of local authorities in helping disadvantaged areas.<ref>''[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2002/feb/01/disadvantaged-areas#2002-02-01T09:52:00Z Hansard]'', HC 6ser vol 379 cols 1160-2.</ref>\n\nDaisley's weight had fallen to seven and a half stone at the time of his treatment, and it was slowly recovering through 2002. However, in November a new cancer was discovered,<ref name=\"Independent obituary\" /> and despite further surgery Daisley was told by his doctors that it was terminal. His colleague [[Barry Gardiner]], MP for [[Brent North (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent North]], announced the prognosis to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] on the last sitting day before Christmas.<ref>''[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2002/dec/19/adjournment-christmas#column_1092 Hansard]'', HC 6ser vol 396 cols 1092-3.</ref> He died from [[colorectal cancer]] aged 45 on 18 June 2003. \n\nIt would be 12 years until Labour held the seat again, because in the [[2003 Brent East by-election|September 2003 by-election]], following Daisley's death, the seat was gained by 29-year old [[Sarah Teather]] of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]. The [[Opposition to the Iraq War|anti-Iraq War vote]] played a key part in gaining the seat. At the time Teather became the youngest MP in the Commons and held the seat and it's successor seat of [[Brent Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent Central]] until [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]], when she stood down and Labour took the seat back again.\n\n==Memorials==\nIn memory of Daisley, the Paul Daisley Trust was established in 2003 to raise awareness of colon cancer and to encourage early diagnosis. It also aims to help people suffering from colon cancer and who are undergoing treatment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pauldaisleytrust.com/default.aspx |title=Paul Daisley Trust |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110207111557/http://pauldaisleytrust.com/default.aspx |archivedate=7 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It holds a regular fundraising celebrity cricket match.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.brent.gov.uk/media.nsf/Files/LBBA-273/$FILE/The%20Brent%20Magazine%20issue%20106%20September%202010.pdf |title=Brent Magazine |issue=September 2010 |page=7 |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> The main hall in Brent Town Hall was named the 'Paul Daisley Hall' in his honour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.brent.gov.uk/officeloc.nsf/pages/lbb-119 |title=Paul Daisley Hall |publisher=Brent Council |accessdate=7 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110105235055/http://www.brent.gov.uk/officeloc.nsf/Pages/LBB-119 |archivedate=5 January 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box| before=[[Ken Livingstone]] | title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Brent East (UK Parliament constituency)|Brent East]] | years=[[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]\u2013[[2003 Brent East by-election|2003]] | after=[[Sarah Teather]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daisley, Paul Andrew}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Brent]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:People who died in office]]\n[[Category:Deaths from colorectal cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParliament and illness:spelling - it's->its", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Daisley"}
{"title_page": "71st Venice International Film Festival", "text_new": "{{short description|Film festival}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Film festival\n|name = <small>71st Venice International Film Festival</small>\n|image = VeniceFilmFestival71poster.jpg\n|caption = Festival poster\n|opening = ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman or (The Unexpected Virtue of Ignorance)]]''\n|closing = ''[[The Golden Era (film)|The Golden Era]]''\n|location = [[Venice]], Italy\n|founded = 1932\n|awards = [[Golden Lion]]: ''[[A Pigeon Sat on a Branch Reflecting on Existence]]''<br>[[Silver Lion]]: [[Andrei Konchalovsky]] (''[[The Postman's White Nights]]'')\n|host = [[Luisa Ranieri]]\n|number = \n|date = 27 August \u2013 6 September 2014\n|website = [http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/ Website]\n| chronology     = Venice Film Festival\n| preceded_by    = [[70th Venice International Film Festival|70th]]\n| followed_by    = [[72nd Venice International Film Festival|72nd]]\n}}\n\nThe '''71st annual [[Venice Film Festival|Venice International Film Festival]]''' took place in Venice, Italy between 27 August to 6 September 2014.<ref name=\"labiennale.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/ |title=71st Venice International Film Festival Line-Up |work=labiennale.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007010534/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/ |archivedate=7 October 2014 }}</ref> The festival opened with [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu|Alejandro G. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]]'s film ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman]]'',<ref name=\"Birdman\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jul/10/birdman-venice-film-festival-opening-night |title=Birdman to hatch on opening night of Venice film festival|accessdate=10 July 2014 |work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=\"BirdmanBBC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28963398 |title=Venice Film Festival kicks off with Birdman |accessdate=28 August 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref> and closed with [[Ann Hui]]'s drama film ''[[The Golden Era (film)|The Golden Era]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/womenandhollywood/ann-huis-the-golden-era-to-close-venice-film-festival |title=Ann Hui's The Golden Era to Close Venice Film Festival |accessdate=28 August 2014 |work=Indiewire |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140824164843/http://blogs.indiewire.com/womenandhollywood/ann-huis-the-golden-era-to-close-venice-film-festival |archive-date=24 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Italian actress [[Luisa Ranieri]] hosted the opening and closing nights of the festival.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/news/08-05.html?back=true |title=Luisa Ranieri to be the host of the 71st Venice Film Festival |accessdate=28 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714133638/http://labiennale.org/en/cinema/news/08-05.html?back=true |archivedate=14 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The Swedish film ''[[A Pigeon Sat on a Branch Reflecting on Existence]]'', directed by [[Roy Andersson]], won the [[Golden Lion]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29098103 |title=Roy Andersson film scoops Venice Golden Lion award |accessdate=2 May 2018 |work=BBC News}}</ref> and [[Joshua Oppenheimer]]'s ''[[The Look of Silence]]'' won the [[Grand Jury Prize (Venice Film Festival)|Grand Jury Prize]].\n\nAmerican filmmakers [[Thelma Schoonmaker]] and [[Frederick Wiseman]] were the recipients of the Lifetime Achievement award.<ref name=\"Lifetime\">{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/news/18-07.html |title=Thelma Schoonmaker and Frederick Wiseman Golden Lions for Lifetime Achievement |accessdate=29 August 2014 |work=labiennale |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903051855/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/news/18-07.html |archive-date=3 September 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> French composer [[Alexandre Desplat]] was the head of the jury for the main competition section.<ref name=\"Variety\"/>\n\nThe festival poster paid tribute to [[Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut]], as it featured the character of [[Antoine Doinel]] portrayed by [[Jean-Pierre L\u00e9aud]] from Truffaut's 1959 [[drama film]] ''[[The 400 Blows]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-film-fest-unveils-poster-716764 |title=Venice Film Fest Unveils Poster for 71st Edition|accessdate=28 August 2014 |work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.swide.com/art-culture/latest-venice-film-festival-2014-news-from-inarritus-birdman-to-classics-lineup/2014/07/22 |title=Venice Film Festival 2014: What we know so far|accessdate=28 August 2014 |work=Swide}}</ref>\n\n==Juries==\n'''Main Competition (Venezia 71)'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/juries/ |title=International Juries of the 71st Venice Film Festival |work=labiennale.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007005126/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/juries/ |archivedate=7 October 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/french-film-composer-alexandre-desplat-to-head-venice-film-festival-jury-1201241763/|title=French Film Composer Alexandre Desplat To Head Venice Film Festival Jury|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=23 June 2014|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Alexandre Desplat]]: French composer (President of Jury)\n*[[Joan Chen]]: Chinese actress and director\n*[[Philip Groning]]: German director\n*[[Jessica Hausner]]: Austrian director\n*[[Jhumpa Lahiri]]: Indian novelist\n*[[Sandy Powell (costume designer)|Sandy Powell]]: English costume designer  \n*[[Tim Roth]]: British actor \n*[[Elia Suleiman]]: Palestinian director\n*[[Carlo Verdone]]: Italian actor and director\n\n'''Horizons (Orizzonti)'''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/venice-film-festival-reveals-lineup-for-its-71st-edition-1201268122/|title=Venice Film Festival Reveals Lineup for Its 71st Edition |accessdate=26 July 2014 |work=Variety}}</ref>\n*[[Ann Hui]]: Hong Kong director (President of Jury)\n*[[Moran Atias]]: Israeli actress\n*[[Pernilla August]]: Swedish actress and director\n*[[David Chase]]: American writer and director \n*[[Mahamat-Saleh Haroun]]: Chadian director \n* Roberto Minervini: Italian director\n* Alin Ta\u015f\u00e7\u0131yan: Turkish critic\n\n'''Opera Prima''' (Venice Award for a Debut Film)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/news/16-06.html|title=Alice Rohrwacher President of the International Jury for the Venice Award for a Debut Film |work=labiennale.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903051851/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/news/16-06.html |archivedate=3 September 2014 }}</ref>\n*[[Alice Rohrwacher]]: Italian director (President of Jury)\n*[[Lisandro Alonso]]: Argentine director\n*[[Ron Mann]]: Canadian filmmaker\n*[[Vivian Qu]]: Chinese filmmaker\n*[[Razvan Radulescu]]: Romanian novelist and film director\n\n==Official selection==\n\n===In Competition===\nThe following films were selected for the main competition:<ref name=\"InComp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/venezia71/ |title=Venezia 71 International competition of feature films |work=labiennale.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006083927/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/71st-festival/line-up/off-sel/venezia71/ |archivedate=6 October 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/07/venice-film-festival-lineup-2014-movie-list/ |title=Venice Film Festival Lineup Announced |accessdate=24 July 2014 |work=Deadline}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"width:95%; margin-bottom:0px\"\n|-\n! English title\n! Original title\n! Director(s)\n! Production country\n|-\n| colspan=2| ''[[99 Homes]]'' || data-so